def mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred):
    """
    Calculate MAPE for given actual data (y_true) and predicted values (y_pred)
    """
    y_true = np.array(y_true)
    y_pred = np.array(y_pred)

    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

Creating time series feature¶

In [237]:
def create_time_series_features(df):
    """
    Creates time series based feature based on datetime index
    """
    df = df.copy()
    df['PowerStatusCode'] = df.PowerStatusCode
    df['date'] = df.index
    if df['WeekNumber'].empty:
      print('in')
      df['WeekNumber'] = df['WeekNumber']
    else:
      print('out')
      df['WeekNumber'] = df['date'].dt.isocalendar().week
    df['hour'] = df.index.hour
    df['dayofweek'] = df.index.dayofweek
    df['year'] = df.index.year
    df['dayofyear'] = df.index.dayofyear
    df['quarter'] = df.index.quarter
    df['dayofmonth'] = df['date'].dt.day
    df['date_offset'] = (df.date.dt.month*100 + df.date.dt.day - 320)%1300
    df['season'] = pd.cut(df['date_offset'], [-1, 300, 602, 900, 1301],
                         labels=['Spring', 'Summer', 'Fall', 'Winter'])
    return df

Significant variables to predict the Total current usage.¶

  • The Week Number, day of week, day of year, day of month and day_offset has more than 0.20 correlation with the response variable. Though the day of year, day of month and day_offset has same correlation, therefore we can take any one of them as a factor.
  • The other variables like phase1, phase2, phase3 and AverageCurrentAmperage are highle correlated but I am assuming the prediction of Total Amperage usage will be based on only dates and power status of the machine in real time as the Total Amperage Usage is the sum of phase1, phase2, phase3. Therefore, I will discard them as x variables for the prediction.

Distribution transformation of the response variable¶

  • Earlier in the data visualisation we saw the distribution of the TotalCurrentUsage that the distribution is skewed and exponetial in nature. Therefore, we will apply log transform of the distribution to be more uniform and then we will check the correlation of x variable with the response variable.

In [251]:
#Pre transformation data
 if CFG.plot_graphs:
    #we are creating a test and eval set generator
    #which can generate 5 test and eval sets when we iterate over it
    #here test size is 1 year and gap between test and train set is 1 day
    tss = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=5, test_size=365, gap=1)
    train = train.sort_index()

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(5, 1, figsize=(15,15), sharex=True)

    fold=0
    for train_idx, eval_idx in tss.split(train):
        train_set=train.iloc[train_idx]
        eval_set=train.iloc[eval_idx]
        train_set['TotalCurrentAmperage'].plot(ax=axs[fold], label="Training Set")
        eval_set['TotalCurrentAmperage'].plot(ax=axs[fold], label='Test Set')
        axs[fold].axvline(eval_set.index.min(), color='black', ls='--')
        fold += 1
    plt.show()

# Distributions
import scipy
# Evaluate several ml models by training on training set and testing on testing set
def evaluate(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    # Names of models
    model_name_list = ['Linear Regression', 'ElasticNet Regression',
                      'Random Forest', 'Extra Trees', 'SVM',
                       'Gradient Boosted', 'XGBoost','Baseline']
    #X_train = X_train.drop(columns='Grade')
    #X_test = X_test.drop(columns='Grade')

    # Instantiate the models
    model1 = LinearRegression()
    model2 = ElasticNet(alpha=1.0, l1_ratio=0.5)
    model3 = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=50)
    model4 = ExtraTreesRegressor(n_estimators=50)
    model5 = SVR(kernel='rbf', degree=3, C=1.0, gamma='auto')
    model6 = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=20)
    model7 = xgb.XGBRegressor(base_score=0.5,
                          booster='gbtree',
                          n_estimators=350,
                          objective='reg:squarederror',
                          max_depth=3,
                          learning_rate=0.01)


    # Dataframe for results
    results = pd.DataFrame(columns=['mae', 'rmse'], index = model_name_list)

    # Train and predict with each model
    for i, model in enumerate([model1, model2, model3, model4, model5, model6, model7]):
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        predictions = model.predict(X_test)

        # Metrics
        mae = np.mean(abs(predictions - y_test))
        rmse = np.sqrt(np.mean((predictions - y_test) ** 2))

        # Insert results into the dataframe
        model_name = model_name_list[i]
        results.loc[model_name, :] = [mae, rmse]

    # Median Value Baseline Metrics
    baseline = np.median(y_train)
    baseline_mae = np.mean(abs(baseline - y_test))
    baseline_rmse = np.sqrt(np.mean((baseline - y_test) ** 2))

    results.loc['Baseline', :] = [baseline_mae, baseline_rmse]

    return results

from numpy import mean
from numpy import std
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from matplotlib import pyplot
def get_models():
  models = dict()
  models['lr'] = LinearRegression()
  models['en'] = ElasticNet(alpha=1.0, l1_ratio=0.5)
  models['rf'] = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=50)
  models['SVM']= SVR(kernel='rbf', degree=3, C=1.0, gamma='auto')
  models['Extra Trees'] = ExtraTreesRegressor(n_estimators=50)
  models['Gradient Boost'] = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=20)
  models['XGBoost'] = xgb.XGBRegressor(base_score=0.5,
                          booster='gbtree',
                          n_estimators=350,
                          objective='reg:squarederror',
                          max_depth=3,
                          learning_rate=0.01)
  return models

# evaluate a given model using cross-validation
def evaluate_model(model, X, y):
	cv = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
	scores = cross_val_score(model, X, y, scoring='r2', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1, error_score='raise')
	return scores

	names.append(name)

        #train the model

        score = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_eval, y_pred)

def create_time_series_features(df):
    """
    Creates time series based feature based on datetime index
    """
    df = df.copy()
    df['PowerStatusCode'] = df.PowerStatusCode
    df['date'] = df.index
    df['WeekNumber'] = df['date'].dt.isocalendar().week
    df['hour'] = df.index.hour
    df['dayofweek'] = df.index.dayofweek
    df['year'] = df.index.year
    df['dayofyear'] = df.index.dayofyear
    df['quarter'] = df.index.quarter
    df['dayofmonth'] = df['date'].dt.day
    df['date_offset'] = (df.date.dt.month*100 + df.date.dt.day - 320)%1300
    df['season'] = pd.cut(df['date_offset'], [-1, 300, 602, 900, 1301],
                         labels=['Spring', 'Summer', 'Fall', 'Winter'])
    return df

Final Coclusion¶

  • The prediction model is able to predict the Total Ampere usage by the machine in a date range provided the power status of the machine. The model has high R-squared value 0.981 and less mean abosulte error of 4.59, therefore it is able to predict future consumption in an error range still providing an outlook with a confidence level. The model performance still can be improved based on the data, model and transformation.
  • For eg:- The data given has only data points of few days in a month. The less variation in the data creates a scenario for underfitting of the model. The time series data can be divided on several parameters like hour, year, seasons and quarter. Hence, it is ideal for any time series models to be trained over several year of data.
  • Based on the amount of data provided we can choose several other models like Profet or any of the neural network models like DNN, CNN or LSTM model to predict time series problems. Here the amount of data had less variance, therefore I choose to work with conventional machine learning models which can work with the less amount of data.
  • One more aspect related to data for time series can go through the transformation to generate trend and seasonality in the data by using different serieses like fourier or laplase transformations, at the same time generate the lag year data for better prediction but our data was only for a month. Here, I haven't taken this approch because I wanted to keep it straight forward without bringing too much of complexity.
